Analysis Objects

Three versions of the original employee data frame are created. One converts all character variables and select rating-type numeric variables to factors. The second dataframe goes a step further and coerces all variables to numeric. The third version is the same as employee_factor with various fields having a log transformation. All are used in different ways during the analysis.

Non-Visualization Variables

Feature Result
descriptiveStats1 Age, MnthInc, PcntSalInc, YrsAtComp
descriptiveStats2 YrsCurrRole, YrsSncPromo, YrsWtCurMgr
EducationData Below College, College, Bachelor, Master, Doctor
GenderData Male, Female
JobRoleData Healthcare Representative, Human Resources, Laboratory Technician, Manager Manufacturing Director, Research Director, Research Scientist, Sales Executive, Sales Representative
ManagerRoleData Manager, Manufacturing Director, Research Director
lm1 linear model for MnthInc and Age
lm2 linear model for log of MnthInc and Age
employee_log copy of employee_factor with log of the MnthInc variable
train_rows data partition of employee_factor
train_subset Subset of employee data for training model
test_subset Subset of employee data for test model
null_model Model with no predictors
full_model Mode with full predictors
glmStep_model Stepwise regression model
employee_normalize a copy of employee_factor with all numeric variables normalized between 0 and 1
knn_model Train model for knn
prediction_knn Predict for knn model
cart_model Classification and Regression tree model on training
employee_rf Random forest model for training data
